Good idea 👍 — this is actually a very good way to verify CI/CD is really deploying the artifacts.

However ⚠️ do not delete the folders themselves, because your systemd services point to those paths.

Instead, delete only the contents inside each folder.

Step 1 — Stop all APIs first

This prevents services from crashing while you delete files.

sudo systemctl stop apigateway
sudo systemctl stop asset-api
sudo systemctl stop attendance-api
sudo systemctl stop employee-api
sudo systemctl stop identity-api
sudo systemctl stop leave-api
sudo systemctl stop masterdata-api
sudo systemctl stop payroll-api
Step 2 — Verify folders

Check again:

cd /opt/alfpro
ls

You should still see:

ApiGateway
Asset.API
Attendance.API
Employee.API
Identity.API
Leave.API
MasterData.API
Payroll.API
Step 3 — Delete ONLY the files inside

Run this carefully:

sudo rm -rf /opt/alfpro/ApiGateway/*
sudo rm -rf /opt/alfpro/Asset.API/*
sudo rm -rf /opt/alfpro/Attendance.API/*
sudo rm -rf /opt/alfpro/Employee.API/*
sudo rm -rf /opt/alfpro/Identity.API/*
sudo rm -rf /opt/alfpro/Leave.API/*
sudo rm -rf /opt/alfpro/MasterData.API/*
sudo rm -rf /opt/alfpro/Payroll.API/*
Step 4 — Confirm they are empty

Example:

ls /opt/alfpro/Payroll.API

Expected output:

(empty)
Step 5 — Trigger CI/CD again

Now push something small:

git commit --allow-empty -m "Test CICD redeploy"
git push

or modify any file.

Jenkins should:

copy publish-artifacts → /opt/alfpro
restart services
